\fs24 \cf0 \
"MyColorPicker" is a sample Cocoa bundle that shows how to write your own custom color picker.  When installed properly, the custom color picker will appear in the system's "Colors" window or 
\f2\fs18 NSColorPanel
\f1\fs24  whenever the user tries to choose a particular color, usually from the "Font" panel or an 
\f2\fs18 NSColorWell
\f1\fs24  control.\
\

\f0\b Summary
\f1\b0 \
The Mac OS X Color pickers come in different varieties.  The built in pickers are: Grayscale-Alpha, Red-Green-Blue, Cyan-Yellow-Magenta-Black, Hue Saturation-Brightness, Custom palette, Custom color list, and Color wheel.  MyColorPicker is a simple illustration of picking the commons colors red, green, blue, white and even gray.\
\

\f0\b Architecture
\f1\b0 \
You build your own custom color picker as a bundle by subclassing 
\f2\fs18 \CocoaLigature0 NSColorPicker.
\f1\fs24  \CocoaLigature1 The NSColorPicker class is an abstract superclass that implements the 
\f2\fs18 NSColorPickingDefault
\f1\fs24  protocol. The NSColorPickingDefault and 
\f2\fs18 NSColorPickingCustom
\f1\fs24  protocols define a way to add color pickers (custom user interfaces for color selection) to the NSColorPanel.\
